## Section 3 â€” Rust: embedded backend usage in live modules

### 3.1  src/openhuman/app_state/ops.rs
Uses effective_backend_api_url + get_session_token to fetch the current user from
GET /auth/me (user profile: id, email, display name). In the fork there is no backend
session and no "current user" in the upstream sense.

Replacement: return a local identity stub. The app_state snapshot should return:
  { "user_id": null, "email": null, "display_name": "Local User", "source": "local" }
or read an optional display name from config (if the user sets one). Remove the
`api_url` and `session_token` dependency entirely from this module.

### 3.2  src/openhuman/config/ops.rs
Exposes `load_and_resolve_api_url()` RPC (openhuman.config_resolve_api_url) which
returns the effective backend URL. The frontend backendUrl.ts calls this.

With the backend gone, this RPC has no valid target. Remove:
  - load_and_resolve_api_url() function
  - The openhuman.config_resolve_api_url RPC registration from all.rs
  - Remove api_url: Option<String> from ConfigSnapshot (the RPC response DTO)
  - Remove api_url handling from ConfigUpdate (the RPC update DTO)
  - Remove the api_url: Option<String> field from the Config struct itself
    (src/openhuman/config/schema/types.rs)
  - Remove the staging_env() / is_staging_app_env() helpers in api/config.rs that
    gate on whether api_url points at staging (only useful for the backend concept)

### 3.3  src/openhuman/credentials/ops.rs  +  session_support module
The credentials module has a session_support submodule that provides get_session_token()
and APP_SESSION_PROVIDER ("app-session"). These exist solely to read/write a backend JWT.

After billing/referral/team/socket/channels-bus are gone there should be zero callers
of get_session_token(). Verify with grep, then delete:
  - src/openhuman/credentials/session_support.rs (or wherever APP_SESSION_PROVIDER lives)
  - Remove the re-export from src/api/jwt.rs (which is being deleted anyway)
  - Remove backend-session RPCs: `auth_store_session`, `auth_get_session_token`,
    backend `auth_get_me`, and backend logout/session-clear paths.
  - Remove the `SessionExpiredSubscriber` if no non-backend provider flow still
    publishes backend-session expiry events. Do not clear native OAuth provider tokens
    just because a cloud/Composio provider returns 401; those have their own refresh/
    reconnect semantics.
  - Keep the rest of credentials/ â€” it is used by the native OAuth token store

### 3.4  src/openhuman/doctor/core.rs
Has a doctor check that calls crate::api::jwt::get_session_token to report whether
the user has a backend session token. The doctor is a diagnostic tool.

Replace: remove the session-token check entirely. Add instead a check that reports
whether at least one cloud_providers entry is configured (so the doctor can flag
"no LLM provider configured") and whether native OAuth tokens exist for Google/GitHub.

### 3.5  src/openhuman/tools/impl/agent/onboarding_status.rs
Has a `has_session_jwt` field populated by get_session_token(). In the fork there is
no backend session.

Replace: hardcode `has_session_jwt: false` (or rename the field to `has_api_key` and
populate it by checking whether any cloud_providers entry has a non-empty API key).

### 3.6  src/openhuman/meet_agent/brain.rs
Uses crate::api â€” audit the specific usage (likely bearer auth for meet transcription
or similar). If it hits the backend, stub or remove the dependency. If it is only using
the URL resolver infrastructure, replace with local config read.

Current audit: this is the backend "live meeting agent" path using
`BackendOAuthClient`; keep the local desktop Meet path (`openhuman.meet_join_call` +
Tauri `meet_call_open_window`) and delete/disable the backend meet-agent path unless
it is rebuilt as local automation.

### 3.7  src/openhuman/inference/voice/cloud_transcribe.rs
Backend voice transcription proxy. Confirm whether this provider is registered in the
voice factory (src/openhuman/voice/factory.rs). If wired in:
  - Remove the cloud/backend transcription provider from the factory
  - Ensure the local Whisper / system transcription paths remain reachable
If it is already unreachable (factory never instantiates it), delete the file and remove
its module declaration.
Also remove the `voice_cloud_transcribe` schema/RPC if there is no direct replacement.

### 3.8  src/openhuman/config/schema/cloud_providers.rs  +  load.rs
Remove AuthStyle::OpenhumanJwt variant from the enum. This was the auth style used by
the legacy "openhuman" sentinel cloud provider entry.

In load.rs, remove migrate_openhuman_jwt_entries() â€” the migration function that rewrote
OpenhumanJwt entries to Bearer on startup. Once the variant is gone from the enum,
the serde deserializer will simply fail to parse old entries (they'll be dropped by the
existing parse_config_with_recovery fallback). If a migration window is desired, convert
existing OpenhumanJwt rows to a disabled/dummy state before removing the variant.

### 3.9  src/openhuman/scheduler_gate/gate.rs
is_signed_out() / set_signed_out() are backend-auth concepts: when the backend returned
a 401, the app set signed_out=true to stop background LLM calls. In the single-user
local fork, the user is never "signed out" in this sense.

  - Make is_signed_out() always return false (a const fn or a one-liner)
  - Remove set_signed_out() â€” it will have no callers once openhuman_backend.rs is gone
  - Keep the rest of scheduler_gate (battery/CPU policy, permit system) â€” it is useful

### 3.10  src/core/observability.rs
Remove is_session_expired_error() and the session-expired string patterns:
  - "SESSION_EXPIRED: backend session not active"
  - "no backend session token; run auth_store_session first"
  - "composio unavailable: no backend session token"
These strings are used as Sentry de-duplication keys. With the backend gone, they will
never be generated. Remove the checks and the corresponding test assertions.

### 3.11  src/openhuman/webhooks/ops.rs
This file is mixed:
  - Local debug/router operations (`list_registrations`, `list_logs`, `register_echo`)
    should stay, but the router must be moved off `SocketManager` first (Section 1.4).
  - Tunnel CRUD/bandwidth operations (`/webhooks/core*`) are backend product routes and
    require a backend JWT. Delete these or replace them with the Composio direct-mode
    local webhook receiver settings/status RPCs.

Frontend consequence: `app/src/services/api/tunnelsApi.ts`, `useWebhooks`,
`TunnelList`, and `WebhooksDebugPanel` must either disappear or stop using a
"backend URL" to build ingress URLs. For direct-mode Composio triggers, the public
URL is the configured ngrok domain plus the local receiver path, not `/webhooks/ingress`.

### 3.12  src/openhuman/channels/controllers/ops.rs
This file still contains backend-managed channel flows even though `channels/bus.rs`
is removable:
  - `telegram_login_start` / `telegram_login_check` create backend link tokens and poll
    `/auth/me` for `telegramId`.
  - `discord_link_start` / `discord_link_check` do the same for Discord.
  - `channel_send_message`, `channel_send_reaction`, `channel_create_thread`,
    `channel_update_thread`, and `channel_list_threads` call backend channel routes.

Replacement:
  - Remove `managed_dm` auth mode unless a native local equivalent is implemented.
  - Keep bot-token/API-key/OAuth modes that route through `channels/runtime/`.
  - If the UI still needs manual send/reaction/thread RPCs, route them through the
    native `Channel` trait/provider APIs instead of BackendOAuthClient.
  - Update frontend channel definitions and config panels so they do not offer
    backend-managed link flows.

### 3.13  src/core/jsonrpc.rs embedded backend callbacks/startup
Remove backend-auth HTTP routes and startup:
  - Telegram registration callback that consumes a backend login token.
  - SocketManager bootstrap and auto-connect on stored backend session token.
  - Any backend-url resolver fallback used only for product-backend calls.

Keep the local JSON-RPC server, `/rpc`, core socket for local renderer events, and
Composio direct webhook receiver routes.

### 3.14  src/openhuman/composio/client.rs and Composio mode
Make Composio direct-only:
  - Change `default_composio_mode()` to `"direct"`.
  - Remove `ComposioClientKind::Backend`, `build_composio_client()`, backend-mode
    docs, and all `/agent-integrations/composio/*` calls.
  - Keep/expand direct v3 client calls against `backend.composio.dev/api/v3/*`.
  - Update tests that currently assert backend-mode failure messages or instantiate
    `IntegrationClient`.
  - Either reject old `mode = "backend"` with a migration warning or migrate it to
    `"direct"` on config load.

This phase should happen before deleting `IntegrationClient`, because the backend
Composio client currently depends on it.

### 3.15  src/openhuman/voice/reply_speech.rs
Reply speech synthesis still proxies the hosted backend's ElevenLabs route with a
session JWT. Choose one:
  a) Replace it with a direct ElevenLabs BYO-key provider stored in AuthService, or
  b) Remove the backend cloud TTS path and the `voice_reply_synthesize` RPC/schema.

Keep `system`, `piper`, and `kokoro` TTS. Do not leave `"cloud"` as a selectable default
unless it has a direct user-key implementation.

