## Section 5 â€” Native channel delivery (the architecture)

This section explains why channels/bus.rs can be deleted cleanly and what the
native delivery path already provides.

### 5.1  Two separate inbound paths (only one is native)

BACKEND SOCKET PATH (being deleted):
  Backend socket â†’ wss://api.tinyhumans.ai/socket.io
    â†’ emits DomainEvent::ChannelInboundMessage (global event bus)
      â†’ ChannelInboundSubscriber in channels/bus.rs handles it
        â†’ runs agent via web channel (start_chat)
          â†’ sends reply back via BackendOAuthClient /channels/{ch}/messages

NATIVE RUNTIME PATH (stays):
  channel.listen(mpsc::Sender<ChannelMessage>)  â€” per native provider
    â†’ run_message_dispatch_loop in channels/runtime/dispatch.rs
      â†’ agent pipeline runs with ctx.channels_by_name[channel]
        â†’ reply via channel.send() / channel.send_draft() / channel.typing()
          â†’ provider-native API directly (Telegram Bot API, Discord REST, etc.)

These are completely separate code paths. channels/bus.rs only responds to events that
the backend socket generates. Once the backend socket is gone, bus.rs is dead code.
The native runtime (channels/runtime/) is unaffected.

Important: `channels/bus.rs` is not the only backend channel code. The managed-DM
controller methods in `channels/controllers/ops.rs` still create backend link tokens,
poll `/auth/me`, and send/reply/thread through backend routes. Remove or replace those
separately (Section 3.12) before deleting `src/api/`.

### 5.2  Native channel capabilities (current state)

TELEGRAM (src/openhuman/channels/providers/telegram/)
  Inbound:  channel_recv.rs â€” long-polling via getUpdates Bot API
  Outbound: channel_ops.rs + channel_send.rs
    âś“ send()         â€” sendMessage (chunked, with Markdown fallback)
    âś“ send_draft()   â€” sendMessage (draft) then editMessageText for progressive updates
    âś“ typing()       â€” sendChatAction(action="typing"), re-fires every 4s
    âś“ reactions      â€” setMessageReaction
    âś“ attachments    â€” sendPhoto, sendDocument, sendAudio, sendVideo
  Auth:     bot_token stored in credentials under "telegram" provider key

DISCORD (src/openhuman/channels/providers/discord/)
  Inbound:  Gateway WebSocket (channel.rs listen()) â€” GUILDS + GUILD_MESSAGES intents
  Outbound: channel.rs send()
    âś“ send()         â€” POST /channels/{id}/messages  (Discord REST v10)
    âś— edit_message() â€” not yet implemented (PATCH /channels/{id}/messages/{id})
    âś— delete_message()â€” not yet implemented (DELETE /channels/{id}/messages/{id})
    âś— typing()       â€” not yet implemented (POST /channels/{id}/typing)
  Auth:     bot_token stored in credentials under "discord" provider key

SLACK (src/openhuman/channels/providers/slack.rs)
  Check current state â€” Slack uses OAuth tokens, likely similar pattern.
  The channels/runtime/startup.rs includes SlackChannel so it is wired in.

EMAIL (src/openhuman/channels/providers/email_channel.rs)
  Standalone SMTP/IMAP â€” no backend dependency.

OTHERS (iMessage, WhatsApp, Signal, IRC, etc.)
  All have local implementations. Audit each for any crate::api usage on a per-file
  basis before deleting src/api/.

WEB CHANNEL (channels/providers/web.rs)
  In-app chat via local event bus. No external API. Not affected.

### 5.3  Discord gaps to fill (before deleting channels/bus.rs)

The bus.rs delete-blocker for Discord is that runtime/dispatch.rs calls
channel.send_draft() and channel.typing() which are not yet implemented.
The Channel trait has default no-op implementations that return Ok(None) / Ok(()).

This is acceptable â€” the runtime falls back to atomic-final delivery (no progressive
edit) when send_draft() returns Ok(None), and silently skips typing() when it no-ops.
The user experience is slightly degraded (no "typing..." indicator, no streaming edit),
but the message is delivered correctly via the existing send() implementation.

TO IMPROVE Discord (not blocking, but recommended):

In src/openhuman/channels/providers/discord/channel.rs, add:

  async fn send_draft(&self, message: &SendMessage) -> anyhow::Result<Option<String>> {
      // POST /channels/{channel_id}/messages â†’ return message id
      let url = format!(
          "https://discord.com/api/v10/channels/{}/messages",
          message.recipient
      );
      let body = json!({ "content": message.content });
      let resp = self.http_client()
          .post(&url)
          .header("Authorization", format!("Bot {}", self.bot_token))
          .json(&body)
          .send().await?;
      // extract .id from response JSON as the draft message id
      let v: serde_json::Value = resp.json().await?;
      Ok(v.get("id").and_then(|id| id.as_str()).map(String::from))
  }

  async fn edit(&self, recipient: &str, message_id: &str, text: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
      // PATCH /channels/{channel_id}/messages/{message_id}
      let url = format!(
          "https://discord.com/api/v10/channels/{}/messages/{}",
          recipient, message_id
      );
      let body = json!({ "content": text });
      self.http_client()
          .patch(&url)
          .header("Authorization", format!("Bot {}", self.bot_token))
          .json(&body)
          .send().await?;
      Ok(())
  }

  async fn typing(&self, recipient: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
      // POST /channels/{channel_id}/typing  â€” no body
      let url = format!(
          "https://discord.com/api/v10/channels/{}/typing",
          recipient
      );
      self.http_client()
          .post(&url)
          .header("Authorization", format!("Bot {}", self.bot_token))
          .send().await?;
      Ok(())
  }

Note: the Channel trait `edit()` and `typing()` default no-ops need to become
override-able. Check whether they already exist on the trait; if not, add them
with default no-op bodies so all existing providers compile unchanged.

### 5.4  Telegram â€” no gaps

Telegram is fully native. The only backend-facing code was in channels/bus.rs which
routed typed messages through the backend relay. The native runtime already delivers
messages via TelegramChannel::send() â†’ sendMessage Bot API. Progressive edits
(editMessageText), typing (sendChatAction), reactions (setMessageReaction), and
attachment sending are all implemented. Nothing to add.

The auth token (bot_token) is read from credentials at channel startup
(channels/runtime/startup.rs constructs TelegramChannel with the stored token).

### 5.5  Web channel â€” no change

The web channel (in-app chat) uses an in-process broadcast bus. It never touched the
backend for message delivery. No changes needed.

### 5.6  Other channels audit checklist

Before deleting src/api/, grep each channel provider for `crate::api`:

  grep -rn "crate::api" src/openhuman/channels/providers/

Any match that is not in bus.rs (already being deleted) represents a provider that
still has a backend dependency. For each match, replace with the equivalent native
API call following the Telegram / Discord patterns above.

Expected result: zero matches outside bus.rs.

